ng, extremely quiet and reliable. Make sure to use low‑profile RAM or check clearance with tall RGB sticks.\n","   - **H100i 240mm AIO**: Better RGB aesthetics and cleaner view of your RAM and motherboard. The O11 Dynamic supports a 240mm radiator easily; for a 7950X, a 240mm AIO is okay, but if you plan heavy all‑core workloads, a 280/360mm (if you ever consider it) would give more thermal headroom.\n","   - For a pure showcase RGB build, most customers prefer the **H100i**.\n","\n","5. **GPU – NVIDIA RTX 4080**\n","   - Excellent for 4K high/ultra with ray tracing + DLSS.\n","   - Fits the performance level of the 7950X nicely.\n","   - The O11 Dynamic has enough space; just double‑check GPU length vs specific card model.\n","\n","6. **Memory – Corsair Vengeance 32GB DDR5 6000 (2×16GB, RGB‑capable)**\n","   - 32GB is ideal for modern AAA gaming + streaming/content creation.\n","   - DDR5‑6000 is a strong spot for AM5 performance.\n","   - Works well with the B650‑PLUS; just enable EXPO in BIOS.\n","\n","7. **Storage**\n","   - **Samsung 980 PRO 2TB NVMe SSD**\n","     - Great primary drive for OS + main games/applications.\n","     - PCIe 4.0, high performance, ideal for this tier of build.\n","   - **Seagate Barracuda 2TB HDD (optional)**\n","     - Good for bulk storage (media, infrequently used games).\n","     - Not required if you prefer an all‑SSD setup, but cost‑effective for large libraries.\n","\n","8. **Power Supply – Corsair RM850x 850W or EVGA SuperNOVA 850 G6**\n","   - 850W is appropriate for Ryzen 9 7950X + RTX 4080 with headroom.\n","   - Both are high‑quality, fully modular, 80+ Gold units.\n","   - Either is fine; pick based on availability/price or brand preference.\n","\n","---\n","\n","**Overall verdict:**  \n","Your parts list is compatible, balanced, and well‑suited for a premium 4K RGB “showcase” build within a ~$6000 full‑setup budget (including high‑end peripherals and monitor).  \n","\n","If you’d like, I can next:\n","- Price out this e